am, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bathe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Wiltshire): habitational name from the city of Bath (see   Bath   1) or from Bathe Barton in Devon, which is named with the same word.","Welsh: variant of   Batha  .","German: from an ancient Germanic personal name formed with the element <i>badu</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bath","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dalbir, Renu, Sandeep, Suneet, Tarlok, Vikram.","English (southern): habitational name from the city of Bath in Somerset, or possibly from Bathe Barton in North Tawton in Devon, or some other minor places so called. The city of Bath is the site of the sumptuous, but in the Middle Ages ruined, Roman baths. The place is named with the dative plural of Old English <i>bæth</i> ‘bath’. In some cases the surname may have originated as a metonymic occupational name for an attendant at a public bath house.","German: variant of   Bathe  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":25,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":50,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":63,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":72,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":117,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth de Bathe was born in 1265, in Somerset, England, her father, Osbert de Bathe, was 15 and her mother, Mrs Osbert de Bathe, was 14. She married William de Weyland II. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in Brandeston, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1265–":"1265–Surnud","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1300–1342":"1300–1342","1250–1296":"1250–1296","1252–Female":"1252–Surnud","1252":"1252","1296":"1296","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1265":"1265","1342":"1342","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Brandeston, Suffolk, England":"Brandeston, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Charsfield, Suffolk, England":"Charsfield, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1265–":"1265–Kuollut","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","1265–Male":"1265–Kuollut","1300–1342":"1300–1342","1250–1296":"1250–1296","1252–Female":"1252–Kuollut","1252":"1252","1296":"1296","1382":"1382","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1265":"1265","1342":"1342","about 1300":"noin 1300","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Brandeston, Suffolk, England":"Brandeston, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Charsfield, Suffolk, England":"Charsfield, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1265–":"1265–Décédée","1265–Female":"1265–Décédée","1265–Male":"1265–Décédé","1300–1342":"1300–1342","1250–1296":"1250–1296","1252–Female":"1252–Décédée","1252":"1252","1296":"12